l) Connections for a fire pump controller; and

m) Voltage indicators and voltage test point devices.

Exception No. 2: A disconnecting means shall not be required when all of the following conditions are met:

a) The panel is part of a group of panels where all panels are part of a single machine. A diagram supplied with the panel shall show this arrangement;

b) Each incoming supply source to the panel is from an upstream industrial control panel that complies with the requirements in Sections 65 – 67. This wiring connection shall be shown in the field wiring diagram for the panel being supplied; and

c) A marking is visible on the outside of the panel with the following statement: "The disconnecting means is located in Panel ___." The blank shall be filled in with the identification of the panel that contains the machine supply circuit disconnecting means.

66.1A A panel complying with the requirements of 66.6.1 Exception No. 2 when provided with a disconnecting means, shall not be required to comply with 66.6.3.

66.6.2 A disconnecting means shall not incorporate a fuseholder that accepts a Class H fuse.

66.6.3 In addition to 30.4, an operating mechanism for the disconnecting means shall be:

a) Readily accessible when the enclosure doors are in the open or closed position;

b) Installed so that its operation is not restricted by the enclosure door while in the open position;

c) Be operable independent of the door position without the use of accessory tools or devices;

d) Able to be locked in the off position independent of the door position; and when locked, closing of the disconnect is not possible.

66.6.4 For such circuits all of the following requirements shall be met:

a) Permanent cautionary marking(s) as required by 55.4 shall be placed adjacent to the supply circuit disconnecting operating handle(s), indicating that it does not de-energize all exposed live parts when it is in the open (off) (isolated) position;

